 global South to its remarketing as a practice of pharmaceutical self-enhancement couched in neoliberal notions of choice. She links the widespread practice of menstrual suppression and other related elective medical interventions to Bahian views of the body as a malleable object that requires constant work. Given this bodily plasticity, and its potentially limitless character, the book considers ways to assess the values attributed to bodily interventions. Plastic Bodies will be of interest to all those working in medical anthropology, gender studies, and sexual and reproductive health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aContraceptive drugsxHealth aspectszBrazilzSalvador. 0aHormones, Sex. 0aMenstrual regulationzBrazilzSalvador. 0aMenstruationxSocial aspectszBrazilzSalvador. 0aMenstruationzBrazilzSalvadorxPrevention. 4aAAA prize winners. 4aDiana Forysthe Prize winner. 4aRosaldo First Book Prize winner. 4afeminist anthropology book prize. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374190zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374190.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles